{
  "query": "What is the evidence for creating adjoining cavities or 'swimthrough' habitats on artificial structures, and how does it differ between subtidal and intertidal zones?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for swimthrough habitats on artificial structures differs significantly between subtidal and intertidal zones. For subtidal artificial structures, there is substantial evidence: two studies examined large swimthrough habitats (>100 mm) showing they supported fish species absent from surfaces without swimthroughs, increased fish species richness and abundance (though effects varied by fish size class, species and survey month), and were used by juvenile spiny lobsters, groupers, sea firs, and adult fishes from five families (action IDs 3456, 3436). Four studies examined small swimthrough habitats (\u2264100 mm) on subtidal structures, finding they had mixed effects on juvenile fish community composition and abundance, supported six fish species absent from control surfaces, and were used by juvenile spiny lobsters, sea firs, adult and juvenile fish (action ID 3436). In contrast, evidence for intertidal artificial structures is limited: no studies were found for large swimthrough habitats (action ID 3438), and only two studies examined small swimthrough habitats, showing they did not alter mobile invertebrate community composition or increase species richness/diversity, but did increase mobile invertebrate abundance and altered invertebrate abundance patterns (action ID 3468).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3456",
    "3436",
    "3438",
    "3468"
  ]
}

