{
  "query": "To improve biodiversity on intertidal artificial structures, how do the outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography compare to creating 'rock pools'?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, creating rock pools on intertidal artificial structures shows significantly stronger biodiversity outcomes compared to creating natural rocky reef topography. \n\nRock pools (Action 3476) were supported by 18 studies with comprehensive positive results: 13 of 16 studies found rock pools supported species that were absent from structure surfaces without pools, with 9 of 12 studies showing higher species diversity and richness compared to structure surfaces without pools. The evidence showed rock pools supported macroalgae, mobile and non-mobile invertebrates, and fish species. \n\nIn contrast, natural rocky reef topography (Action 3435) was examined by only two studies with limited positive outcomes. One study found no increase in combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness, and only mixed effects on barnacle and mobile invertebrate abundances depending on site. While one study reported colonization by macroalgae and limpets using shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions, the overall evidence base is much smaller and less positive than for rock pools.\n\nThe rock pool intervention appears to be more effective at enhancing biodiversity on intertidal artificial structures based on the substantially larger and more consistently positive evidence base.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3435",
    "3476",
    "3438",
    "3467"
  ]
}

