{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating large hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures vary between subtidal zones in Israel and Sweden versus intertidal zones in Australia and Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "For subtidal zones, three studies examined hole habitats (>50mm) on artificial structures in Israel and Sweden. These studies found that creating holes altered community composition and supported species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitat features. Two of the three studies found increased species richness/diversity, while results were mixed for abundance outcomes - one study off Sweden found no increase in mobile invertebrate and fish abundance, but an increase in brown crab abundance was observed.\n\nFor intertidal zones, five studies examined hole habitats in southeast Australia, UK, Netherlands, and Israel. These studies consistently found that hole habitats supported macroalgae and/or non-mobile invertebrate species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitat features. All three studies measuring richness/diversity found increases in combined macroalgae and invertebrate species diversity and/or richness on structure surfaces. However, abundance results were mixed - studies in Netherlands and Australia found no increase in macroalgal or invertebrate abundance, while one Australian study found mixed effects on limpet abundance depending on shore level and site. Hole habitats were used by sea slugs, urchins and octopuses according to one Australian study.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3434",
    "3467"
  ]
}

