{
  "query": "What are the general ecological effects of simultaneously creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges, or ledges on artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "The ecological effects of simultaneously creating grooves and small protrusions, ridges, or ledges (1-50 mm) on artificial structures have been extensively studied across marine environments. For intertidal structures, 16 studies across multiple locations including Singapore Strait, USA, Australia, Hong Kong, Israel, Spain, and the UK demonstrate varied ecological impacts. Community composition effects are mixed - three of five controlled studies found these features altered macroalgae and invertebrate community composition, while two studies showed mixed effects depending on site conditions and feature arrangements. Species diversity and richness generally increased in six of eleven controlled studies, with mixed effects in five studies depending on factors like groove/ledge dimensions, shore level, and species groups. Population abundance effects also varied - two studies found increased combined abundance when features were partially-covered with water-retaining and light-shading covers, while other studies showed mixed or no significant effects on macroalgae, invertebrates, and fish abundances depending on environmental conditions and site characteristics.\n\nFor subtidal structures, three studies in Israel, UK, and Spain found these microhabitat features generally enhanced biodiversity. One controlled study found altered community composition and increased species richness and diversity, while another showed mixed effects on species richness depending on surface orientation. The features supported colonization by macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrates, with abundance effects varying by surface orientation. These microhabitat modifications consistently provide colonization opportunities for species that would otherwise be absent from smooth artificial structure surfaces, creating more complex habitat heterogeneity that can enhance marine biodiversity in both intertidal and subtidal environments.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3474",
    "3452"
  ]
}

