{
  "query": "In what ways do the reported outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography on artificial structures differ between intertidal studies in the UK and subtidal studies in Italy?",
  "relevant_summary": "The outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography on artificial structures differ significantly between intertidal studies in the UK and subtidal studies in Italy. In the UK intertidal studies (action 3435), creating natural rocky reef topography on artificial structures had no significant effect on combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness, but showed mixed effects on barnacle and mobile invertebrate abundances depending on the site. The natural topography was colonized by macroalgae and limpets, with limpets actively using shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions created by the topography. In contrast, the Italian subtidal study (action 3446) found that creating natural rocky reef topography on subtidal artificial structures did not increase the abundance of juvenile canopy macroalgae that settled onto structure surfaces, regardless of the topography depth. The intertidal UK studies demonstrated more complex outcomes with species utilizing the created habitats behaviorally, while the subtidal Italian study showed limited effects on algal settlement, with no reported community-level responses or behavioral outcomes.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3435",
    "3446"
  ]
}

