{"query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating small versus large protrusions, ridges or ledges on intertidal artificial structures compare?", "summary": "Small features (1-50 mm) and large features (>50 mm) on intertidal artificial structures show different biodiversity outcomes. Small protrusions, ridges, and ledges had mixed effects on community composition - some studies found no changes while others reported effects varying by site and habitat arrangement (Action ID: 3462, 3464, 3474). Large features showed more consistent positive outcomes, with large ledges increasing species diversity and abundance of macroalgae, microalgae, and invertebrates (Action ID: 3465). However, large protrusions and ridges did not consistently increase species richness compared to small features (Action ID: 3463, 3465).

For specific organism groups, small ledges supported lower mobile invertebrate richness than adjacent grooves but had similar fish richness (Action ID: 3464). Large ledges increased mussel and limpet abundances but not barnacles, and enhanced juvenile salmon feeding activity (Action ID: 3465). The effectiveness depended on feature arrangement - combining grooves with small ridges/ledges often produced better outcomes than individual features alone (Action ID: 3474).

When both small and large features were tested together, results were mixed, with effectiveness varying by site, habitat height/depth, and species groups (Action ID: 3465, 3474).", "action_ids": ["3464", "3465", "3462", "3463", "3474"]}

