{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating short flexible habitats compare with long flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both short flexible habitats (1\u201350 mm) and long flexible habitats (>50 mm) on subtidal artificial structures show mixed effects on biodiversity outcomes. Long flexible habitats (Action ID: 3451) supported macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats, with higher combined macroalgae and invertebrate biomass compared to structure surfaces without flexible habitats. Deeper flexible habitats supported higher biomass than shallower ones. However, long flexible habitats had mixed effects on fish species richness, mobile and non-mobile invertebrate abundance, and fish abundance depending on factors such as species group, survey timing, flexible habitat length and density. Short flexible habitats (Action ID: 3450) had mixed effects on invertebrate community composition depending on density, length, and site, with no increase in invertebrate species richness observed. Invertebrate abundance showed mixed effects depending on survey week, species group, habitat length, or site, and seahorse abundance also varied by survey week. Both habitat types were used by seahorses, though this was only documented for long flexible habitats.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3451",
    "3450"
  ]
}

